# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hibernate-orm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate is free software that is distributed under the Apache License.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Versions prior to 7.0.0.Beta4 were distributed under the GNU Lesser General Public License 2.1.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate's primary feature is mapping from Java classes to database tables, and mapping from Java data types to SQL data types.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate also provides data query and retrieval facilities.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] It generates SQL calls and relieves the developer from the manual handling and object conversion of the result set.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate ORM is a certified compatible implementation of the industry-standard Jakarta Persistence (formerly Java Persistence API) and Jakarta Data specifications.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] The mapping of Java classes to database tables is implemented by the configuration of an XML file or by using Java Annotations.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] When using an XML file, Hibernate can generate skeleton source code for the persistence classes.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] This is auxiliary when annotations are used.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate can use the XML file or the Java annotations to maintain the database schema.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] There are provided facilities to arrange one-to-many and many-to-many relationships between classes.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In addition to managing associations between objects, Hibernate can also manage reflexive associations wherein an object has a one-to-many relationship with other instances of the class type.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate supports the mapping of custom value types.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Mapping informs the ORM tool of what Java class object to store in which database table.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate provides a SQL inspired language called Hibernate Query Language (HQL) for writing SQL-like queries against Hibernate's data objects.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] *Criteria Queries* are provided as an object-oriented alternative to HQL.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Criteria Query is used to modify the objects and provide the restriction for the objects.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] HQL (Hibernate Query Language) is the object-oriented version of SQL.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] It generates database independent queries so that there is no need to write database-specific queries.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Without this capability, changing the database would require individual SQL queries to be changed as well, leading to maintenance issues.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate provides transparent persistence for Plain Old Java Objects (POJOs).
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] The only strict requirement for a persistent class is a no-argument constructor, though not necessarily **`public`**.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Proper behavior in some applications also requires special attention to the `equals(Object obj)` and `hashCode()` methods in the `Object` classes.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate recommends providing an identifier attribute, and this is planned to be a mandatory requirement in a future release.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Collections of data objects are typically stored in Java collection classes, such as implementations of the `Set` and `List` interfaces.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Java generics, introduced in Java 5, are also supported.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate can be configured to lazy load associated collections.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Lazy loading is the default as of Hibernate 3.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Related objects can be configured to *cascade* operations from one object to the other.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] For example, a parent `Album` class object can be configured to cascade its `save` and `delete` operations to its child `Track` class objects.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate can be used both in standalone Java applications and in Java EE applications using servlets, EJB session beans, and JBI service components.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] It can also be included as a feature in other programming languages.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] For example, Adobe integrated Hibernate into version 9 of ColdFusion (which runs on J2EE app servers) with an abstraction layer of new functions and syntax added into CFML.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In Hibernate jargon, an *entity* is a stand-alone object in Hibernate's persistent mechanism which can be manipulated independently of other objects.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In contrast, a *component* is subordinate to an entity and can be manipulated only with respect to that entity.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] For example, an Album object may represent an entity; but the Tracks object associated with the Album objects would represent a *component* of the Album entity, if it is assumed that Tracks can only be saved or retrieved from the database through the Album object.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Unlike J2EE, Hibernate can switch databases.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Hibernate was started in 2001 by Gavin King with colleagues from Cirrus Technologies as an alternative to using EJB2-style entity beans.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] The original goal was to offer better persistence capabilities than those offered by EJB2; by simplifying the complexities and supplementing certain missing features.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In early 2003, the Hibernate development team began Hibernate2 releases, which offered many significant improvements over the first release.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] (now part of Red Hat) later hired the lead Hibernate developers in order to further its development.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In 2005, Hibernate version 3.0 was released.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Key features included a new Interceptor/Callback architecture, user defined filters, and JDK 5.0 Annotations (Java's metadata feature).
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] As of 2010, Hibernate 3 (version 3.5.0 and up) was a certified implementation of the Java Persistence API 2.0 specification via a wrapper for the Core module which provides conformity with the JSR 317 standard.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In Dec 2011, Hibernate Core 4.0.0 Final was released.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In December 2012, Hibernate ORM 4.1.9 Final was released.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In Mar 2013, Hibernate ORM 4.2 Final was released.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In December 2013, Hibernate ORM 4.3.0 Final was released.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In September 2015, Hibernate ORM 5.0.2 Final was released.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] It has improved bootstrapping, hibernate-java8, hibernate-spatial, Karaf support.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In November 2018, Hibernate ORM 5.1.17 Final was released.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] This is the final release of the 5.1 series.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In October 2018, Hibernate ORM 5.3 Final was released.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] It featured Java Persistence API 2.2 inheritance caching.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In December 2018, Hibernate ORM 5.4.0 Final was released.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In March, 2022, Hibernate ORM 6.0.0 Final was released, a "major redesign [which] has touched almost every subsystem of Hibernate, including the APIs, mapping annotations, and the query language".
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] The last of the 6.x series is version 6.6.x with 6.6.0.Final released in August 2024 and is in limited support in 2026.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] The 6.6 series support Java 11, 17, 21 and 25 and is compatible with Jakarta Persistence 3.1 and Jakarta EE 10.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] In May 2025, Hibernate ORM 7.0.0 Final was released, with support for Jakarta Persistence 3.2 and Jakarta Data 1.0.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] 7.1.0.Final was released in August 2025 and 7.2.0.Final in December 2025 both 7.1 and 7.2 series support Java 17, 21 and 25 and are compatible with Jakarta Persistence 3.2 and Jakarta EE 11.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] The Hibernate API is provided in the Java package `org.hibernate`.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] The `org.hibernate.SessionFactory` interface is the native equivalent version of the JPA's standard `EntityManagerFactory`.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] The `org.hibernate.Session` interface represents a Hibernate session, i.e., the main point of the manipulation performed on the database entities.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] The latter activities include (among the other things) managing the persistence state (transient, persisted, detached) of the objects, fetching the persisted ones from the database and the management of the transaction demarcation.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] A `Session` is intended to last as long as the logical transaction on the database.
[src:hibernate-orm/hibernate-framework] Due to the latter feature, `Session` implementations are not expected to be thread safe nor to be used by multiple clients.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The final release date of the JPA 1.0 specification was 11 May 2006 as part of Java Community Process JSR 220.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The JPA 2.0 specification was released 10 December 2009 (the Java EE 6 platform requires JPA 2.0).
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The JPA 2.1 specification was released 22 April 2013 (the Java EE 7 platform requires JPA 2.1).
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The JPA 2.2 specification was released in the summer of 2017.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The reference implementation for JPA 1 and 2 was EclipseLink.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Jakarta Persistence 3.1 was released in the spring of 2022 as part of Jakarta EE 10.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Jakarta Persistence 3.2 was released in spring 2024, targeting inclusion in Jakarta EE 11.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] EclipseLink and Hibernate are compatible implementations.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] A persistence entity is a lightweight Java class with its state typically persisted to a table in a relational database.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Instances of such an entity correspond to individual rows in the table.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Entities typically have relationships with other entities, and these relationships are expressed through object/relational mapping (ORM) metadata.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] This metadata may be specified directly in the entity class file by using annotations or in a separate XML descriptor file distributed with the application.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] An example entity class with ORM metadata declared using annotations (import statements and setters/getters are omitted for simplicity).
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The `@Entity` annotation declares that the class represents an entity.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] `@Id` declares the attribute which acts as the primary key of the entity.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Additional annotations may be used to declare additional metadata (for example changing the default table name in the `@Table` annotation), or to create associations between entities.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The Jakarta Persistence Query Language (JPQL; formerly Java Persistence Query Language) makes queries against entities stored in a relational database.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Queries resemble SQL queries in syntax but operate against entity objects rather than directly with database tables.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Prior to the introduction of EJB 3.0 specification, many enterprise Java developers used lightweight persistent objects provided by either persistence frameworks (such as Hibernate) or data access objects (DAO) instead of by using entity beans.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Thus, many of the features originally presented in third-party persistence frameworks were incorporated into the Java Persistence API, and projects such as Hibernate and TopLink Essentials have become implementations of the Java Persistence API specification.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The EJB 3.0 specification (itself part of the Java EE 5 platform) included a definition of the Java Persistence API.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] However, developers do not need an EJB container or a Java EE application server to run applications that use this persistence API.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Future versions of the Java Persistence API will be defined in a separate JSR and specification rather than in the EJB JSR/specification.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The Java Persistence API replaces the persistence solution of EJB 2.0 CMP (Container-Managed Persistence).
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The Java Persistence API was developed in part to unify the Java Data Objects API and the EJB 2.0 Container Managed Persistence (CMP) API.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Most products supporting each of the two APIs support the Java Persistence API.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The Java Persistence API specifies persistence only for relational database management systems by focusing on object-relational mapping (ORM).
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Some JPA providers support other database models, though this is outside the scope of JPA's design.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The Java Data Objects specification supports ORM as well as persistence to other types of database models, for example, flat file databases and NoSQL databases, including document databases, graph databases any many other datastores.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Hibernate, founded by Gavin King, provides an open source object-relational mapping framework for Java.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Versions 3.2 and later provide an implementation for the Java Persistence API.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] King represented JBoss on JSR 220, the JCP expert group charged with developing JPA.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] This led to ongoing controversy and speculation surrounding the relationship between JPA and Hibernate.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Sun Microsystems stated that ideas came from several frameworks, including Hibernate and Java Data Objects.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The Spring Data JPA is an implementation of the repository abstraction that is a key building block of domain-driven design based on the Java application framework Spring.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] It transparently supports all available JPA implementations and supports CRUD operations as well as the convenient execution of database queries.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Development of a new version of JPA 2.0 was started in July 2007 in the Java Community Process as JSR 317.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] JPA 2.0 was approved as final on 10 December 2009.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The focus of JPA 2.0 was to address features that were present in some of the popular ORM vendors but could not gain consensus approval for JPA 1.0.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Development of JPA version 2.1 began in July 2011 as JSR 338.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] JPA 2.1 was approved as final on 22 May 2013.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] Development of JPA 2.2, a maintenance release, began in 2017 under JSR 338.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The maintenance review was approved on 19 June 2017.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] The JPA was renamed as Jakarta Persistence in 2019 and version 3.0 was released in 2020.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] This included the renaming of packages and properties from javax.persistence to jakarta.persistence.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] It is part of Jakarta EE 10, and thus requires at least Java 11 to run.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] It adds better UUID handling, various new JPQL functions for math and date/time handling, and other small changes.
[src:hibernate-orm/jakarta-persistence] It introduced a large number of API improvements along with some improvements to the query language.
[src:hibernate-orm/java-persistence-query-language] The **Jakarta Persistence Query Language** (**JPQL**; formerly Java Persistence Query Language) is a platform-independent object-oriented query language defined as part of the Jakarta Persistence (JPA; formerly Java Persistence API) specification.
[src:hibernate-orm/java-persistence-query-language] JPQL is used to make queries against entities stored in a relational database.
[src:hibernate-orm/java-persistence-query-language] It is heavily inspired by SQL, and its queries resemble SQL queries in syntax, but operate against JPA entity objects rather than directly with database tables.
[src:hibernate-orm/java-persistence-query-language] In addition to retrieving objects (`SELECT` queries), JPQL supports set based `UPDATE` and `DELETE` queries.
[src:hibernate-orm/java-persistence-query-language] Example JPA Classes, getters and setters omitted for simplicity.
[src:hibernate-orm/java-persistence-query-language] JPQL supports named parameters, which begin with the colon (`:`).
[src:hibernate-orm/java-persistence-query-language] JPQL is based on the Hibernate Query Language (HQL), an earlier non-standard query language included in the Hibernate object-relational mapping library.
[src:hibernate-orm/java-persistence-query-language] Hibernate and the HQL were created before the JPA specification.
[src:hibernate-orm/java-persistence-query-language] As of Hibernate 3 JPQL is a subset of HQL.
